Summary of  Phase  Transition  Processes 	  (melting, vaporization, and sublimation) require an input of energy; they are endothermic. Processes in which attractive interactions are formed (freezing, condensation, and deposition) release energy, so they are exothermic. The amount of energy necessary to melt one mole of a substance is known as the molar heat of fusion. Similarly, the amount of energy necessary to vaporize one mole of a substance is referred to as the molar heat of vaporization. The values of these parameters are given for water in the following table, along with the specific heats exhibited by water in its solid, liquid, and gaseous forms. TABLE 17.2: 
